        <h3>The Science Behind the Shy Plant</h3>

        <p>Mimosa pudica is native to Central and South America but is now found in tropical and subtropical regions worldwide. The plant’s leaves are highly sensitive and collapse inward when touched, giving the impression of a timid response. This movement is a defense mechanism known as thigmonasty—a reaction to physical stimuli.

         The process is driven by changes in turgor pressure within the plant's cells. When stimulated, the cells at the base of the leaflets release water, causing the leaves to lose stiffness and fold. This movement happens within seconds and can be triggered by:</p>
        <ul>
         <li>A light touch</li>
         <li>Vibrations</li>
         <li>Wind</li>
         <li>Sudden temperature changes</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Why Does the Shameplant React This Way?</h3>
        <p>Scientists believe this unique response evolved as a survival strategy. The rapid movement may startle herbivores, making the plant appear less appetizing. Additionally, folding its leaves may reduce water loss and protect it from environmental stressors like heavy rain or strong winds.</p>
